{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/food-for-thought-paper-tuesday-bffb85506bfd", "time": 1683002383.815371, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/food-for-thought-paper-tuesday-bffb85506bfd/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Food for Thought \u2014 Paper Tuesday. New matrix factorization for fast\u2026 | by Zixuan Zhang | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Food for Thought \u2014 Paper Tuesday", "description": "Every Tuesday I highlight an interesting paper that I came across in research or work. I hope that my review can help you get the juiciest part of the paper under 2 minutes! Countless projects have\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Every Tuesday I highlight an interesting paper that I came across in research or work. I hope that my review can help you get the juiciest part of the paper under 2 minutes!", "Countless projects have proved that matrix factorization (MF) is no double one of the most powerful recommendation generation algorithms since the 2006 Netflix Prize competition. The key idea is to factorize the user-item interaction matrix into two children matrices with lower ranks.", "By decomposing the interaction matrix, MF somehow extracts latent features that are surprisingly good at describing both users and items. If you want to know more about the algorithm itself, here\u2019s a list of resources that you can take advantage of:", "One issue with traditional MF in practice is that when the matrix becomes huge (imagine Amazon has to decompose its user-item interaction matrix, it\u2019s gonna be a millions by millions matrix), it becomes infeasible to update the latent features regularly (when a user makes a new purchase, we want this transaction to slightly affect the latent vectors). I came across this paper by Xiangnan He, Hanwang Zhang, Min-Yen Kan, and Tat-Seng Chua called Fast Matrix Factorization for Online Recommendation with Implicit Feedbacks. They proposed a new method called eALS, which significantly speeds up the online update process.", "The authors proposed a new way to speed up ALS by caching values that are repetitively used and a new trick to avoid solving the whole problem every time new updates arrive.", "To make online models more effective at responding to the latest inputs, the authors proposed a weight strategy.", "Another interesting proposal in the paper is what they called item-oriented weighting on missing data, which can incorporate domain knowledge into the algorithm. For instance, if a user has never purchased a trending item, the item should be treated more like negative feedbacks comparing to an unviewed rare item.", "The authors empirically demonstrated that the confidence parameter c (see the picture above) does improve the performance to some extent.", "Effects of new interaction parameter W (higher W means more weights on new interactions)", "The most exciting result to me is the significant time complexity improvement. The proposed new method is 100+ faster than ordinary Alternating Least Square, a well known method to solve matrix factorization (It makes sense because ALS needs to solve the whole problem every time it needs to update the latent vectors while eALS only works on the additional data and at cost of higher space complexity).", "I was working on a recommendation system myself over my summer internship and online update was a headache for me. I am glad that this paper brings us one step closer to models that can be easily updated and incorporates more domain knowledges.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "New grad SDE at some random company. Student at Columbia & USC. I know how hard learning CS outside the classroom can be, so I hope my blog can help!"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fbffb85506bfd&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav---------------------------